statement:
Find the interval of convergence of the following series:

\begin{align*}\sum_{k=1}^\infty a_k(x-1)^k\end{align*}

where $\displaystyle a_k > 0$ for $k=1,2,\dots$ and

\begin{align*}\sum_{k=1}^\infty \left(\frac{a_k}{a_{k+1}} - \frac{a_{k+1}}{a_{k+2}}\right) = \frac{a_1}{a_2}\end{align*}

sols:
Let $\displaystyle b_{n} = a_{n}(x-1)^{n}$ Ratio test gives

\begin{align*}\lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{b_{n+1}}{b_{n}} = \lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{a_{n+1}|x-1|}{a_{n}}\end{align*}

Next, the partial summation from the convergent sum given to us in the
problem statement tells us that

\begin{align*}
\sum_{k=1}^n \left(\frac{a_k}{a_{k+1}} - \frac{a_{k+1}}{a_{k+2}}\right) 
&= \left(\frac{a_1}{a_{2}} - \frac{a_{2}}{a_{3}}\right) + \left(\frac{a_2}{a_{3}} - \frac{a_{3}}{a_{4}}\right) + ... + \left(\frac{a_{n}}{a_{n+1}} - \frac{a_{n+1}}{a_{n+2}}\right)\\
&= \frac{a_1}{a_{2}} + \left(- \frac{a_{2}}{a_{3}} + \frac{a_2}{a_{3}}\right) + \left( - \frac{a_{3}}{a_{4}} + \frac{a_{3}}{a_{4}}\right) + ... + \left(-\frac{a_{n}}{a_{n+1}} + \frac{a_{n}}{a_{n+1}}\right)+ \left( - \frac{a_{n+1}}{a_{n+2}}\right)\\
&= \frac{a_{1}}{a_{2}} - \frac{a_{n+1}}{a_{n+2}}\end{align*}

Since these partial sums converge to $\frac{a_{1}}{a_{2}}$, we know that

\begin{align*}\lim_{n \to \infty} \frac{a_{n+1}}{a_{n+2}} = 0\end{align*}

and hence by relabeling

\begin{align*}\lim_{n \to \infty} \frac{a_{n}}{a_{n+1}} = 0\end{align*}

Thus the reciprocal limit from the ratio test above diverges and so the
limit in the ratio test diverges unless $x=1$. Thus the interval of
convergence is just the point $\displaystyle I = \{1\}$.
